<div class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-lg-8">
        <h2 class="mb-4">Understanding Menopause</h2>

        <div class="card mb-4">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">What is Menopause?</h4>
            <p>
              Menopause is the natural biological process that marks the end of
              a woman's menstrual cycles. It's officially diagnosed after you've
              gone 12 months without a menstrual period. Menopause can happen in
              your 40s or 50s, but the average age in the United States is 51.
            </p>
            <p>
              The transition to menopause is called perimenopause, which can
              last several years. During this time, hormonal fluctuations can
              cause various physical and emotional symptoms before menstruation
              finally stops.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h4>Stages of Menopause</h4>

        <div class="card mb-4">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h5 class="card-title">Perimenopause</h5>
            <p>
              <strong>Typical age range:</strong> Late 30s to late 40s/early 50s
            </p>
            <p><strong>Duration:</strong> 4-10 years (average 4 years)</p>
            <p>
              During perimenopause, your ovaries gradually produce less
              estrogen. This transition typically begins several years before
              menopause. Characteristics include:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>
                Irregular periods (longer or shorter cycles, heavier or lighter
                flow)
              </li>
              <li>Beginning of hot flashes for some women</li>
              <li>Sleep disturbances</li>
              <li>Mood changes</li>
              <li>Declining fertility, though pregnancy is still possible</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="card mb-4">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h5 class="card-title">Menopause</h5>
            <p>
              <strong>Definition:</strong> The point when you haven't had a
              menstrual period for 12 consecutive months
            </p>
            <p><strong>Average age:</strong> 51 in the United States</p>
            <p>
              At this stage, your ovaries have stopped releasing eggs and
              producing most of their estrogen. Menopause isn't a prolonged
              state - it's technically just the milestone marking the end of
              your reproductive years.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="card mb-4">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h5 class="card-title">Postmenopause</h5>
            <p>
              <strong>Duration:</strong> The rest of your life after menopause
            </p>
            <p>
              This is the stage after menopause when many symptoms ease for most
              women, though some effects of low estrogen continue. During this
              time:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>
                Hot flashes and night sweats typically decrease in frequency and
                intensity
              </li>
              <li>Vaginal dryness and urinary issues may continue or worsen</li>
              <li>
                Risk of certain health conditions increases (osteoporosis, heart
                disease)
              </li>
              <li>
                Protection through healthy lifestyle becomes increasingly
                important
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h4 class="mt-5">Common Symptoms</h4>
        <p>
          Every woman's experience with menopause is unique. Some women have few
          or no symptoms, while others experience significant changes that
          affect their quality of life. Common symptoms include:
        </p>

        <div class="row">
          <div class="col-md-6">
            <div class="card mb-4">
              <div class="card-body">
                <h5 class="card-title">Hot Flashes & Night Sweats</h5>
                <p>
                  A sudden feeling of warmth spreading through the upper body,
                  often accompanied by flushed skin and sweating. Night sweats
                  are hot flashes that occur during sleep.
                </p>
                <p><strong>Management tips:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Dress in layers you can remove</li>
                  <li>
                    Identify triggers (spicy foods, alcohol, caffeine, stress)
                  </li>
                  <li>Keep your bedroom cool at night</li>
                  <li>Use cooling products designed for menopause</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="col-md-6">
            <div class="card mb-4">
              <div class="card-body">
                <h5 class="card-title">Sleep Disturbances</h5>
                <p>
                  Many women experience insomnia or disrupted sleep during
                  perimenopause and menopause, often due to night sweats but
                  sometimes independently.
                </p>
                <p><strong>Management tips:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Maintain a consistent sleep schedule</li>
                  <li>Create a cool, dark, comfortable sleep environment</li>
                  <li>Avoid screens before bedtime</li>
                  <li>Practice relaxation techniques</li>
                  <li>Exercise regularly (but not too close to bedtime)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="col-md-6">
            <div class="card mb-4">
              <div class="card-body">
                <h5 class="card-title">Mood Changes</h5>
                <p>
                  Hormonal fluctuations can contribute to mood swings,
                  irritability, anxiety, or depression.
                </p>
                <p><strong>Management tips:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Regular exercise</li>
                  <li>Stress management techniques</li>
                  <li>Adequate sleep</li>
                  <li>Social connections and support</li>
                  <li>Professional support if mood changes are severe</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="col-md-6">
            <div class="card mb-4">
              <div class="card-body">
                <h5 class="card-title">Vaginal Dryness & Urinary Issues</h5>
                <p>
                  Decreased estrogen can lead to thinning and drying of vaginal
                  tissues, which may cause discomfort during intercourse and
                  increase urinary symptoms.
                </p>
                <p><strong>Management tips:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Over-the-counter vaginal moisturizers</li>
                  <li>Water-based lubricants during intercourse</li>
                  <li>Regular sexual activity to improve blood flow</li>
                  <li>Pelvic floor exercises</li>
                  <li>
                    Discuss prescription options with your healthcare provider
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="col-lg-4">
        <div class="info-card">
          <div class="info-card-content">
            <h4>Treatment Options</h4>
            <p>Several approaches can help manage menopause symptoms:</p>
            <h5 class="mt-3">Lifestyle Modifications</h5>
            <ul class="list-group list-group-flush">
              <li class="list-group-item">Regular physical activity</li>
              <li class="list-group-item">
                Balanced nutrition rich in calcium and vitamin D
              </li>
              <li class="list-group-item">Stress management techniques</li>
              <li class="list-group-item">
                Avoiding trigger foods and beverages
              </li>
              <li class="list-group-item">Maintaining a healthy weight</li>
              <li class="list-group-item">Quitting smoking</li>
            </ul>

            <h5 class="mt-3">Hormone Therapy</h5>
            <p>
              For some women, hormone therapy (HT) effectively manages symptoms
              like hot flashes and vaginal dryness. This involves taking
              estrogen or a combination of estrogen and progesterone.
            </p>
            <div class="alert alert-info">
              <strong>Note:</strong> Hormone therapy has benefits and risks.
              Discuss with your healthcare provider to determine if it's
              appropriate for you.
            </div>

            <h5 class="mt-3">Non-Hormonal Medications</h5>
            <ul class="list-group list-group-flush">
              <li class="list-group-item">
                Certain antidepressants for hot flashes
              </li>
              <li class="list-group-item">
                Gabapentin for hot flashes and sleep disturbances
              </li>
              <li class="list-group-item">Clonidine for hot flashes</li>
              <li class="list-group-item">
                Medications for specific symptoms like vaginal dryness
              </li>
            </ul>

            <h5 class="mt-3">Complementary Approaches</h5>
            <p>Some women find relief with:</p>
            <ul class="list-group list-group-flush">
              <li class="list-group-item">Acupuncture</li>
              <li class="list-group-item">Mindfulness meditation</li>
              <li class="list-group-item">Yoga</li>
              <li class="list-group-item">Tai chi</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="info-card mt-4">
          <img
            src="https://pixabay.com/get/g74466375526f1bf790c05fc73edcbf1885a68888a5ce9b296a7dccb37593f3f247983a100f81913e64541c2dec3679efe3288b54a6857c600ef89225c2d6e7a5_1280.jpg"
            alt="Healthy Aging Woman"
            class="info-card-img"
          />
          <div class="info-card-content">
            <h4>Long-Term Health Considerations</h4>
            <p>
              After menopause, certain health risks increase due to lower
              estrogen levels:
            </p>
            <ul class="list-group list-group-flush">
              <li class="list-group-item">
                <strong>Osteoporosis:</strong> Bone density decreases more
                rapidly after menopause
              </li>
              <li class="list-group-item">
                <strong>Heart Disease:</strong> Risk increases postmenopause
              </li>
              <li class="list-group-item">
                <strong>Weight Changes:</strong> Metabolism slows and fat
                distribution changes
              </li>
              <li class="list-group-item">
                <strong>Urinary Health:</strong> Increased risk of urinary tract
                infections
              </li>
            </ul>
            <p class="mt-3">
              Regular health screenings and preventive care become increasingly
              important during this life stage.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section" style="background-color: var(--light-color)">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="text-center mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="accordion" id="menopauseFAQ">
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingOne">
          <button
            class="accordion-button"
            type="button"
            data-bs-toggle="collapse"
            data-bs-target="#collapseOne"
            aria-expanded="true"
            aria-controls="collapseOne"
          >
            How do I know if I'm in perimenopause?
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div
          id="collapseOne"
          class="accordion-collapse collapse show"
          aria-labelledby="headingOne"
          data-bs-parent="#menopauseFAQ"
        >
          <div class="accordion-body">
            The most common sign of perimenopause is irregular periods. You
            might skip periods, experience shorter or longer cycles, or have
            heavier or lighter bleeding than usual. Other common signs include
            hot flashes, sleep disturbances, mood changes, vaginal dryness, and
            decreased fertility. If you're in your 40s and experiencing these
            symptoms, you may be in perimenopause. A healthcare provider can
            perform tests to check hormone levels, though these fluctuate
            significantly during perimenopause, so diagnosis is often based on
            symptoms and age.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingTwo">
          <button
            class="accordion-button collapsed"
            type="button"
            data-bs-toggle="collapse"
            data-bs-target="#collapseTwo"
            aria-expanded="false"
            aria-controls="collapseTwo"
          >
            How long do menopause symptoms last?
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div
          id="collapseTwo"
          class="accordion-collapse collapse"
          aria-labelledby="headingTwo"
          data-bs-parent="#menopauseFAQ"
        >
          <div class="accordion-body">
            The duration of menopause symptoms varies significantly from woman
            to woman. On average, women experience symptoms for 4-8 years, but
            some women have symptoms for just a few months while others have
            them for more than 10 years. Hot flashes typically peak within the
            first two years after your final period and then gradually decrease
            in frequency and intensity. However, some symptoms like vaginal
            dryness tend to worsen over time without treatment. About 10% of
            women continue to have hot flashes well into their 70s and beyond.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingThree">
          <button
            class="accordion-button collapsed"
            type="button"
            data-bs-toggle="collapse"
            data-bs-target="#collapseThree"
            aria-expanded="false"
            aria-controls="collapseThree"
          >
            Is hormone therapy safe?
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div
          id="collapseThree"
          class="accordion-collapse collapse"
          aria-labelledby="headingThree"
          data-bs-parent="#menopauseFAQ"
        >
          <div class="accordion-body">
            The safety of hormone therapy (HT) depends on many factors,
            including your age, health history, and how long you've been
            postmenopausal. Current guidelines suggest that HT is generally safe
            for healthy women who are experiencing moderate to severe menopause
            symptoms and are:
            <ul>
              <li>Under 60 years old</li>
              <li>Within 10 years of menopause onset</li>
              <li>
                Without a history of certain conditions like breast cancer,
                heart disease, stroke, or blood clots
              </li>
            </ul>
            The risks increase the longer you use HT and as you age. For most
            women with significant symptoms, the benefits of short-term HT (less
            than 5 years) outweigh the risks. It's important to have a detailed
            discussion with your healthcare provider about your personal risk
            factors and to reassess the need for HT annually.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingFour">
          <button
            class="accordion-button collapsed"
            type="button"
            data-bs-toggle="collapse"
            data-bs-target="#collapseFour"
            aria-expanded="false"
            aria-controls="collapseFour"
          >
            What lifestyle changes can help manage menopause symptoms?
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div
          id="collapseFour"
          class="accordion-collapse collapse"
          aria-labelledby="headingFour"
          data-bs-parent="#menopauseFAQ"
        >
          <div class="accordion-body">
            Several lifestyle adjustments can help manage menopause symptoms:
            <ul>
              <li>
                <strong>Regular exercise:</strong> Aim for at least 150 minutes
                of moderate activity per week to reduce hot flashes, improve
                sleep, enhance mood, and maintain bone density.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Balanced diet:</strong> Focus on fruits, vegetables,
                whole grains, lean proteins, and healthy fats. Reduce processed
                foods, sugar, and salt.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Adequate calcium and vitamin D:</strong> These nutrients
                support bone health. Women over 50 need about 1,200 mg of
                calcium and 600-800 IU of vitamin D daily.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Limit triggers:</strong> Identify and reduce consumption
                of foods and beverages that trigger hot flashes, such as spicy
                foods, caffeine, and alcohol.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Stress management:</strong> Practice techniques like
                deep breathing, meditation, yoga, or tai chi to reduce stress,
                which can worsen menopause symptoms.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Quit smoking:</strong> Smoking can trigger hot flashes
                and increases your risk for heart disease, osteoporosis, and
                many cancers.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Maintain a healthy weight:</strong> Being overweight can
                increase the frequency and severity of hot flashes.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Practice good sleep hygiene:</strong> Keep your bedroom
                cool, establish a regular sleep schedule, and create a relaxing
                bedtime routine.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

